It had been ages since I saw any of the films in this four-movie edition of Disney films.  I had heard a lot about Darby O'Gill, but had never seen it until now.  It's a respectable film, as are the others.  Typical Disney canned technical issues are offset by extravagant sets, special effects, good acting and decent direction.

The technical aspect that holds back a better film is the continued use of processed monaural sound for the films, giving them a real unnatural quality.  Fortunately Disney caught up to the 20th and then 21st centuries, so their films don't sound so "processed".

To me these films are more for nostalgia value than anything else.  If I were a young boy again I might get impatient with the "old" and "fake" looking special effects, but I might stay interested for the stories themselves.

Darby O'Gill features a very young, handsome Sean Connery and some excellent special effects; Happiest Millionaire tells a true story of instustrialist Biddle features Fred MacMurray and Greer Garson; the Gnome-Mobile has great special effects, and the One and Only Genuine, Original Family Band gives a refreshing glimpse at yesteryear with its patriotism and Americana ~ a very worthwhile collection for lovers of Disney feature films.

I got this specifically for Darby O'gill which is a nostalgic movie I remember from my childhood. I enjoyed it. It's a well-done fairy tale with some amazing effects for the time. There are extras on the disk that show you how they did a lot of the little people effects pre-CGI and green screen. If not for that, this would probably be a one-star review.

Gnome-Mobile is pretty awful overall with very characters and a weak story. It ends with a really sexist scene at the end where a bunch of women are in competition over who will marry a guy and then he's supposed to be forced to marry the winner. This is supposed to be funny but I found it more disturbing, and I certainly don't think kids should see something like that.
